Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 2 TBSP (4
TBSP for 4 servings). Dice @tomato{2}(diced). Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%oz}(roughly chopped).
Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1}(cored, deseeded, and diced).

In a #small bowl{}, combine minced onion, half the tomatoes, half the cilantro, and a
splash of @red wine vinegar{5%tsp} to taste. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine half the @sour cream{3%tbsp} with ¼ tsp
@southwest spice blend{1%tbsp} (½ tsp for 4 servings). (You'll use the rest of the sour
cream and Southwest Spice Blend in the next step.) Season with salt and pepper. Add
@water{1%tsp} at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

> Pat chicken dry with paper towels if using chicken instead of beef.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add
@ground beef{10%oz}; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, until
browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}.
Wipe out pan.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in large pan over medium-high heat. Add green
pepper, sliced onion, and a big pinch of salt. Cook, stirring occasionally, until
browned and tender, ~{7-8%minutes}.

Stir in remaining tomatoes, remaining Southwest Spice Blend, and 2 TBSP water. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until tomatoes are softened and mixture is thickened and
saucy, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> If veggie mixture seems dry, add up to 2 TBSP more water.

Remove from heat; stir in remaining cilantro and remaining sour cream. Season with
salt and pepper.

> Use pan used for chicken or beef here.

Place @flour tortillas{2} on a clean work surface; sprinkle one half of each tortilla
with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Top with veggie filling, then sprinkle with @pepper jack cheese{1/2%cup}.

Fold tortillas in half to create quesadillas.

> Add chicken or beef to tortillas along with veggie filling.

Wash out pan used for veggie filling; return to medium-high heat with a drizzle of
olive oil.

Add quesadillas; cook until tortillas are golden brown and cheeses have melted,
~{2-4%minutes} per side.

> Depending on the size of your pan, you may need to work in batches.

Cut quesadillas into wedges; divide between #plates{} and top with @guacamole{4%tbsp}
and salsa. Drizzle with crema and serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.